### **ApiTools.cs** — tool class wrapping a REST API

```csharp
using System.ComponentModel;
using ModelContextProtocol.Server;

[McpServerToolType]
public class ApiTools(IHttpClientFactory httpFactory, ILogger<ApiTools> logger)
{
    [McpServerTool, Description("Get a user by their unique identifier.")]
    public async Task<string> GetUser(
        [Description("The user's unique ID (e.g. 42)")] int userId,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        logger.LogInformation("Fetching user {UserId}", userId);
        var client = httpFactory.CreateClient("api");
        return await client.GetStringAsync($"/users/{userId}", cancellationToken);
    }

    [McpServerTool, Description("Search users by name. Returns matching results as JSON.")]
    public async Task<string> SearchUsers(
        [Description("Name or partial name to search for")] string query,
        [Description("Max results to return (1-100, default 10)")] int limit = 10,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        var client = httpFactory.CreateClient("api");
        return await client.GetStringAsync(
            $"/users?q={Uri.EscapeDataString(query)}&limit={limit}",
            cancellationToken);
    }

    [McpServerTool(ReadOnly = false, Destructive = false),
     Description("Create a new user with the given name and email.")]
    public async Task<string> CreateUser(
        [Description("Full name of the user")] string name,
        [Description("Email address")] string email,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        var client = httpFactory.CreateClient("api");
        var response = await client.PostAsJsonAsync(
            "/users", new { name, email }, cancellationToken);
        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        return await response.Content.ReadAsStringAsync(cancellationToken);
    }
}
```

---

### How DI works for MCP tools

The SDK has two injection styles:

**1. Constructor injection** (shown above) — use a **non-static** class with a primary constructor. Services (`IHttpClientFactory`, `ILogger<T>`, etc.) are resolved once when the tool class is instantiated. Best when multiple tools share the same dependencies.

**2. Method parameter injection** — use a **static** class. DI services appear as method parameters and are resolved per-call:

```csharp
[McpServerToolType]
public static class ApiTools
{
    [McpServerTool, Description("Get a user by ID.")]
    public static async Task<string> GetUser(
        [Description("User ID")] int userId,
        IHttpClientFactory httpFactory,       // ← injected, hidden from schema
        CancellationToken cancellationToken)   // ← also hidden
    { ... }
}
```

**Key rule:** The SDK auto-injects these types and **hides them from the tool schema** exposed to the LLM:

| Type | Purpose |
|------|---------|
| `CancellationToken` | Cooperative cancellation |
| `IMcpServer` | Server instance (notifications, logging) |
| `IProgress<ProgressNotificationValue>` | Progress reporting |
| Any DI-registered service | `IHttpClientFactory`, `ILogger<T>`, custom services |

Only parameters with `[Description]` appear in the schema the LLM sees. Register your services in `Program.cs` (`AddHttpClient`, `AddSingleton<T>`, etc.) and the SDK wires them up automatically — no `[FromServices]` or special attributes needed.
